hands_on_practices.solution:
We start from the one-loop crossed-box correction factor  
$$
C_{\rm box}
= i\,e^2\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega}{2\pi}
\int\frac{d^3\vec k}{(2\pi)^3}
\frac{1}{\omega^2-\vec k^2+i\epsilon}
\;\frac{2m_e}{m_e^2v^2-\vec k^2-2m_e\omega-i\delta}\,.
$$

1.  Isolate the Coulomb (potential) region by performing the $\omega$-integral first.  
   Using the partial-fraction identity
   $$
   \frac1{\omega^2-\vec k^2+i\epsilon}
   =\frac1{2|\vec k|}\Bigl[\frac1{\omega-|\vec k|+i\epsilon}
                    -\frac1{\omega+|\vec k|-i\epsilon}\Bigr],
   $$
   only the pole at \,$\omega=|\vec k|-i0\,$ in the first term produces the $1/v$ singularity.  Evaluating the residue gives
   $$
   \int\frac{d\omega}{2\pi}
   \frac1{\omega^2-\vec k^2+i\epsilon}\,
   \frac{2m_e}{m_e^2v^2-\vec k^2-2m_e\omega-i\delta}
   \;\Bigl|_{\omega=|\vec k|}
   =\frac{i\,m_e}{|\vec k|\,[\,m_e^2v^2-\vec k^2-2m_e|\vec k|-i0\,]}\,.
   $$

2.  In the nonrelativistic (threshold) limit $|\vec k|\sim m_ev\ll m_e$, one may expand
   $$
   m_e^2v^2-\vec k^2-2m_e|\vec k|\;\simeq\;-2m_e\,(|\vec k|-m_ev)\,,
   $$
   so that the remaining $d^3\vec{k}$ integral reduces to
   $$
   C_{\rm box}
   \;\simeq\;i\,e^2\int\!\frac{d^3k}{(2\pi)^3}
     \frac{m_e}{|\vec k|\bigl[-2m_e(|\vec k|-m_ev)-i0\bigr]}
   =-\;i\,\frac{e^2}{2}\int\!\frac{d^3k}{(2\pi)^3}\,
     \frac{1}{|\vec k|\,(|\vec k|-m_ev+i0)}.
   $$

3.  Switch to spherical coordinates, $d^3\vec{k}=4\pi\,k^2dk$, and note the key distributional identity
   $$
   \int_0^\infty\!\frac{k^2\,dk}{k\,(k-p+i0)}
   =\int_0^\infty\!\frac{k\,dk}{k-p+i0}
   =\mathrm{PV}\!\int_0^\infty\!\frac{k\,dk}{k-p}
     +i\pi\frac{p}{2}
   \;\longrightarrow\;i\,\frac{\pi p}{2},
   \quad p\equiv m_ev.
   $$
   Hence
   $$
   C_{\rm box}
   =-\;i\,\frac{e^2}{2}\;\frac{4\pi}{(2\pi)^3}\;
     \Bigl[i\,\frac{\pi\,m_ev}{2}\Bigr]
   =\frac{e^2}{4\pi}\,\frac{\pi}{v}
   =\frac{\pi\,\alpha}{v}\,,
   $$
   where we used $e^2=4\pi\alpha$.

Therefore the leading Coulomb singularity in the crossed-box amplitude is
$$
C_{\rm box}=\frac{\pi\,\alpha}{v}\,.
$$
